<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n01119b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n01" href="#n01119b">N01 (VI.B.10)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n01all.htm#n01119b"> 119(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ soft shoe dancer</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Now Germany is <font color="green">[teeming]</font> with &ldquo;steptanzers&rdquo; which is German for clogdancers. Most of the youths, after demobilisation following the Armistice, learned &ldquo;steptanzering&rdquo; by mail from a correspondence school, run by a couple of <mark>soft-shoe American dancers</mark>, operating from Berlin <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The male &ldquo;steptanzers&rdquo; frequently help the hat-check bandits assisting patrons into their overcoats, thus collecting a few tips. <small> <a name="IT27jan23" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#IT27jan23"><cite title="source">Irish Times</cite></a> (27 January 1923) 6/7 [German Cabaret Craze. / By Henry Wales. / Essen, Friday.]</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c05168c" href="c05all.htm#c05168c">VI.C.05:168(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
